 ('406', '287', '10', '654', 'en_us', '38', '', '{\"typeId\":\"10\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Audio Sermons\",\"slug\":\"audio-sermons\",\"postDate\":1505209560,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"3\":\"\",\"13\":{\"288\":{\"type\":\"sermonAudio\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"currentSermons\":[\"937\",\"923\",\"913\",\"911\",\"875\",\"858\",\"856\",\"840\",\"832\",\"798\",\"796\",\"794\",\"792\",\"790\",\"788\",\"289\",\"302\",\"303\",\"304\",\"803\",\"802\",\"805\",\"807\",\"809\",\"811\",\"813\",\"815\",\"817\",\"819\"]}}},\"11\":\"\",\"12\":\"<p>Never miss the message. Play our sermons directly in your browser or download them for listening on-the-go. Already heard the message? Refresh your memory and listen again.<\\/p>\",\"27\":\"\",\"70\":\"\"}}', '2017-12-18 16:11:58', '2017-12-18 16:11:58', 'b2d66250-5259-44f3-93ae-74c928c4168b'),
 ('407', '355', '10', '654', 'en_us', '11', '', '{\"typeId\":\"10\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Liturgy\",\"slug\":\"liturgy\",\"postDate\":1505416800,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"3\":\"\",\"13\":{\"563\":{\"type\":\"generalSection\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"<p>Among those blessings are the gift of the Eucharist itself and the opportunity it provides for healing, both individual and collective. At Transfiguration the Eucharistic Liturgy&nbsp;(worship) offers a foundation for and pathway to deeper faith regardless of spiritual background or condition. In the words of the great Spiritual, \\u201clet us break bread together on our knees,\\u201d humbly asking God for forgiveness and for the strength and courage to do His will in our daily lives.<br><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><em>by Bill Glew<\\/em><\\/p>\"}}},\"11\":[\"938\"],\"12\":\"<p>The Gospels speak of troubled people seeking to touch the hem of Christ\\u2019s garment, that they might be healed. Christ\\u2019s garment is no more, but before He left this earth He gave us what our prayerbook calls \\u201ca foretaste of thy heavenly banquet\\u201d \\u2013 Holy Eucharist (or Communion or Mass), instituted at the Last Supper and celebrated every Sunday and weekday at the Church of The Transfiguration. \\u201cCelebrate\\u201d is the right word, because every Eucharist is a corporate giving of thanks to God for our many blessings.<\\/p>\",\"27\":\"\",\"70\":\"\"}}', '2017-12-20 21:07:25', '2017-12-20 21:07:25', 'b64b88bd-6551-4f38-bf9c-e91b6f07b8c9'),
 ('408', '943', '9', '654', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"654\",\"title\":\"Come to the Manger\",\"slug\":\"come-to-the-manger\",\"postDate\":1513878622,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"28\":{\"new1\":{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"<p>When I was a boy, there were two events that confirmed that Christmas was about to happen. The first was my Uncle Louis&nbsp; method of adjusting a tree taller than the living room. Unlike others confronted with excess tree footage, my Uncle Louis removed several inches from the tree top, rather than the bottom to make a perfect fit. For me, my uncle\\u2019s method was magical. Uncle Louis\\u2019 alteration was like the \\u201cNutcracker\\u201d ballet tree that continued growing beyond all heights and into the sky,<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The other and more significant Christmas event was my nonna\\u2019s (grandmother), Josephine Bonasera-Vento, arrangement of the Christmas manger beneath Uncle Louis\\u2019 Christmas tree. Purchased in the early day\\u2019s of the depression, Nonna\\u2019s nativity figures were made of chalkware&nbsp; (moulded from plaster of Paris) and faded from handling. The figures were softly painted in colors not to dissimilar to doll prizes won at fairs and carnivals.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>My nonna\\u2019s nativity figures included: wise men; shepherds, sheep, a donkey, camels, and a&nbsp; cow. Inside the straw covered cardboard manger were the three most important figures: Mary, Jospeh and the infant Jesus. I can vividly remember so many Christmas\\u2019 laying on the floor beneath the sprawling tree branches starring at the miniature figures and imagining I was amongst them.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>When I first saw Transfiguration\'s collection of nativity figures (many over a hundred years old) sprawled about the sanctuary, I felt something missing. It took me two years before suggesting moving the figures and display them collectively in a tableau to the side of the sanctuary. So with my two decorating cohorts, Maryann Wlock and Maurice Antaya, we created a version of the nativity with a background of Christmas trees. As beautiful as the new scene was received, something was still not quite right. What was missing was the building - a manger.<\\/p>\"}},\"new3\":{\"type\":\"figure\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"image\":[\"941\"],\"altAttribute\":\"\",\"caption\":\"\",\"credit\":\"Leo Mascaro\",\"enlarge\":\"\",\"orientation\":\"horizontal\"}},\"new2\":{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"<p>Putting pencil to paper, I drafted an idea for the new Transfiguration Christmas creche. After sharing and getting approval from Father John David, Maryann and Maurice, and&nbsp;&nbsp;I met with a carpenter who translated the drawing into a manger. Together, Maryann, Maurice, Tyrone (our verger) and I have now given the holy family and friends a new home.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Each time that I look at the new Transfiguration Christmas manger, I will be reminded of my nonna, Uncle Louis and my childhood memories of Christmas. For the longest time, I wondered if Uncle Louis purposely lopped off the tree top to create an illusion that through the ceiling a tree searched for a star to cast a beam of light on nonna\\u2019s Christmas figures. Boun Natale!<\\/p>\"}},\"new4\":{\"type\":\"figure\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"image\":[\"942\"],\"altAttribute\":\"Leo Mascaro\",\"caption\":\"\",\"credit\":\"\",\"enlarge\":\"\",\"orientation\":\"horizontal\"}}},\"25\":[\"940\"],\"26\":\"Ray Vento\",\"27\":\"Leo Moscaro\",\"70\":\"http:\\/\\/www.leonardomascaro.com\\/\"}}', '2017-12-21 17:50:22', '2017-12-21 17:50:22', '557a3def-6cb5-483d-af97-d2ddc58c66ba'),
 ('409', '943', '9', '654', 'en_us', '2', '', '{\"typeId\":\"9\",\"authorId\":\"654\",\"title\":\"Come to the Manger\",\"slug\":\"come-to-the-manger\",\"postDate\":1513878600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"28\":{\"944\":{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"<p>When I was a boy, there were two events that confirmed that Christmas was about to happen. The first was my Uncle Louis&nbsp; method of adjusting a tree taller than the living room. Unlike others confronted with excess tree footage, my Uncle Louis removed several inches from the tree top, rather than the bottom to make a perfect fit. For me, my uncle\\u2019s method was magical. Uncle Louis\\u2019 alteration was like the \\u201cNutcracker\\u201d ballet tree that continued growing beyond all heights and into the sky,<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The other and more significant Christmas event was my nonna\\u2019s (grandmother), Josephine Bonasera-Vento, arrangement of the Christmas manger beneath Uncle Louis\\u2019 Christmas tree. Purchased in the early day\\u2019s of the depression, Nonna\\u2019s nativity figures were made of chalkware&nbsp; (moulded from plaster of Paris) and faded from handling. The figures were softly painted in colors not to dissimilar to doll prizes won at fairs and carnivals.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>My nonna\\u2019s nativity figures included: wise men; shepherds, sheep, a donkey, camels, and a&nbsp; cow. Inside the straw covered cardboard manger were the three most important figures: Mary, Jospeh and the infant Jesus. I can vividly remember so many Christmas\\u2019 laying on the floor beneath the sprawling tree branches starring at the miniature figures and imagining I was amongst them.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>When I first saw Transfiguration\'s collection of nativity figures (many over a hundred years old) sprawled about the sanctuary, I felt something missing. It took me two years before suggesting moving the figures and display them collectively in a tableau to the side of the sanctuary. So with my two decorating cohorts, Maryann Wlock and Maurice Antaya, we created a version of the nativity with a background of Christmas trees. As beautiful as the new scene was received, something was still not quite right. What was missing was the building - a manger.<\\/p>\"}},\"945\":{\"type\":\"figure\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"image\":[\"941\"],\"altAttribute\":\"\",\"caption\":\"\",\"credit\":\"Leo Mascaro\",\"enlarge\":\"\",\"orientation\":\"vertical\"}},\"946\":{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"<p>Putting pencil to paper, I drafted an idea for the new Transfiguration Christmas creche. After sharing and getting approval from Father John David, Maryann and Maurice, and&nbsp;&nbsp;I met with a carpenter who translated the drawing into a manger. Together, Maryann, Maurice, Tyrone (our verger) and I have now given the holy family and friends a new home.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Each time that I look at the new Transfiguration Christmas manger, I will be reminded of my nonna, Uncle Louis and my childhood memories of Christmas. For the longest time, I wondered if Uncle Louis purposely lopped off the tree top to create an illusion that through the ceiling a tree searched for a star to cast a beam of light on nonna\\u2019s Christmas figures. Boun Natale!<\\/p>\"}},\"947\":{\"type\":\"figure\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"image\":[\"942\"],\"altAttribute\":\"Leo Mascaro\",\"caption\":\"\",\"credit\":\"\",\"enlarge\":\"\",\"orientation\":\"horizontal\"}}},\"25\":[\"940\"],\"26\":\"Ray Vento\",\"27\":\"Leo Moscaro\",\"70\":\"http:\\/\\/www.leonardomascaro.com\\/\"}}', '2017-12-21 17:52:42', '2017-12-21 17:52:42', '459b7e2f-6385-41a6-9108-ea9c387afacb'),
 ('410', '943', '9', '654', 'en_us', '3', '', '{\"typeId\":\"9\",\"authorId\":\"654\",\"title\":\"Come to the Manger\",\"slug\":\"come-to-the-manger\",\"postDate\":1513878600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"28\":{\"944\":{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"<p>When I was a boy, there were two events that confirmed that Christmas was about to happen. The first was my Uncle Louis&nbsp; method of adjusting a tree taller than the living room. Unlike others confronted with excess tree footage, my Uncle Louis removed several inches from the tree top, rather than the bottom to make a perfect fit. For me, my uncle\\u2019s method was magical. Uncle Louis\\u2019 alteration was like the \\u201cNutcracker\\u201d ballet tree that continued growing beyond all heights and into the sky,<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The other and more significant Christmas event was my nonna\\u2019s (grandmother), Josephine Bonasera-Vento, arrangement of the Christmas manger beneath Uncle Louis\\u2019 Christmas tree. Purchased in the early day\\u2019s of the depression, Nonna\\u2019s nativity figures were made of chalkware&nbsp; (moulded from plaster of Paris) and faded from handling. The figures were softly painted in colors not to dissimilar to doll prizes won at fairs and carnivals.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>My nonna\\u2019s nativity figures included: wise men; shepherds, sheep, a donkey, camels, and a&nbsp; cow. Inside the straw covered cardboard manger were the three most important figures: Mary, Jospeh and the infant Jesus. I can vividly remember so many Christmas\\u2019 laying on the floor beneath the sprawling tree branches starring at the miniature figures and imagining I was amongst them.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><br><\\/p>\"}},\"945\":{\"type\":\"figure\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"image\":[\"941\"],\"altAttribute\":\"\",\"caption\":\"\",\"credit\":\"Leo Mascaro\",\"enlarge\":\"\",\"orientation\":\"vertical\"}},\"946\":{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"<p>When I first saw Transfiguration\'s collection of nativity figures (many over a hundred years old) sprawled about the sanctuary, I felt something missing. It took me two years before suggesting moving the figures and display them collectively in a tableau to the side of the sanctuary. So with my two decorating cohorts, Maryann Wlock and Maurice Antaya, we created a version of the nativity with a background of Christmas trees. As beautiful as the new scene was received, something was still not quite right. What was missing was the building - a manger.<\\/p><p>Putting pencil to paper, I drafted an idea for the new Transfiguration Christmas creche. After sharing and getting approval from Father John David, Maryann and Maurice, and&nbsp;&nbsp;I met with a carpenter who translated the drawing into a manger. Together, Maryann, Maurice, Tyrone (our verger) and I have now given the holy family and friends a new home.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Each time that I look at the new Transfiguration Christmas manger, I will be reminded of my nonna, Uncle Louis and my childhood memories of Christmas. For the longest time, I wondered if Uncle Louis purposely lopped off the tree top to create an illusion that through the ceiling a tree searched for a star to cast a beam of light on nonna\\u2019s Christmas figures. Boun Natale!<\\/p>\"}},\"947\":{\"type\":\"figure\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"image\":[\"942\"],\"altAttribute\":\"Leo Mascaro\",\"caption\":\"\",\"credit\":\"\",\"enlarge\":\"\",\"orientation\":\"horizontal\"}}},\"25\":[\"940\"],\"26\":\"Ray Vento\",\"27\":\"Leo Moscaro\",\"70\":\"http:\\/\\/www.leonardomascaro.com\\/\"}}', '2017-12-21 17:53:15', '2017-12-21 17:53:15', 'f3ede7a2-1bd4-43e9-a8a6-fb300b5401f9'),
